    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-08-27T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-08-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="265"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d265">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.5/3–2054</note>
                <head>No. 265<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the Counselor (<persName corresp="#p_MDII1"
                            type="from">MacArthur</persName>) to <persName type="to">Harold N.
                            Waddell</persName> of the Bureau of Far Eastern Affairs</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d265fn1">Sent to Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DJF1"
                            >Dulles</persName> as an attachment to <ref target="#d262">Document
                            262</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-08-27">August 27,
                            1954</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Attached file.</item>
                </list>
                <p>I have read the attached memorandum from <gloss target="#t_FE1">FE</gloss>
                    recommending a mutual defense treaty with the Republic of China, and while I
                    recognize that a very good case can be made for the conclusion of such an
                    arrangement, I nonetheless have doubts as to the desirability of pursuing such a
                    course at this particular time.</p>
                <p>As a practical matter, I think the various statements which have been made by top
                    officials in this country, including the highest level, have made it quite clear
                    to the Chinese Nationalists, the Chinese Communists, and others, that we would
                    use our military forces to oppose any Chinese Communist attempt to attack
                    Formosa.</p>
                <p>To sum it up, I believe that the considerations which governed the decision with
                    respect to this question last March and April are still valid.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MDII1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">D Mac</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
